description.p:
For example, conservative amino acid changes may be made, which although they alter the primary sequence of the protein or peptide, do not normally alter its function. Conservative amino acid substitutions typically include substitutions within the following groups:



    

glycine, alanine;

valine, isoleucine, leucine;

aspartic acid, glutamic acid;

asparagine, glutamine;

serine, threonine;

lysine, arginine;

phenylalanine, tyrosine.


Modifications (which do not normally alter primary sequence) include in vivo, or in vitro chemical derivatization of polypeptides, e.g., acetylation, or carboxylation. Also included are modifications of glycosylation, e.g., those made by modifying the glycosylation patterns of a polypeptide during its synthesis and processing or in further processing steps; e.g., by exposing the polypeptide to enzymes which affect glycosylation, e.g., mammalian glycosylating or deglycosylating enzymes. Also embraced are sequences which have phosphorylated amino acid residues, e.g., phosphotyrosine, phosphoserine, or phosphothreonine.

claim.claim-text:
1. A method of isolating a DNA encoding a protein which binds to a platelet antigen, said method comprising:
generating a shuffled library comprising: 1) mixing DNAs from at least a first γκ phage display library and a second γλ phage display library, wherein said first γκ phage display library comprises at least one virus vector that comprises DNA encoding a heavy and light chain isolated from panning a population of phage against a platelet antigen and said second γλ phage display library comprises at least one virus vector that comprises DNA encoding a heavy and light chain isolated from panning a population of phage against said platelet antigen, further wherein said panning a population of phage against said platelet antigen comprises adding a magnetic label to cells bearing said platelet antigen on their surface, thereby producing magnetically labeled cells; incubating said phage display library with said magnetically labeled cells in the presence of an excess of unlabeled cells which do not express said platelet antigen to form a mixture, whereby said at least one virus vector binds to said magnetically labeled cells; isolating magnetically labeled cells from said mixture, whereby said at least one virus vector is isolated from said mixture, and obtaining DNA encoding a heavy and light chain from said isolated virus vector; 2) dissociating said DNA encoding the heavy chains from said at least one virus vector from said first γκ phage display library and said at least one virus vector from said second γλ phage display library using a restriction endonuclease thereby generating a mixture of dissociated heavy chain DNA segments and dissociated vectors encoding a light chain and re-ligating the dissociated heavy chain DNA segment into a dissociated vector encoding a light chain thereby generating a hybrid virus vector encoding a light chain and a heavy chain that is not encoded by a single vector in the first and second phage display library;
incubating said hybrid virus vector with magnetically labeled cells in the presence of an excess of non-labeled cells which do not express said platelet antigen to form a mixture, whereby said hybrid virus vector binds to said magnetically labeled cells;
isolating magnetically labeled cells from said mixture, whereby said hybrid virus vector is isolated from said mixture; and
isolating said DNA encoding said protein from said isolated hybrid virus vector.

2. A method of isolating a multi-subunit protein which binds to an antigen-bearing moiety, said method comprising
generating a phage display library comprising a plurality of virus vectors, wherein a first of said virus vectors comprises a first heterologous DNA encoding an Fab comprising a γ1κ subunit and expresses said γ1κ subunit on the surface thereof, and wherein a second of said virus vectors comprises a second heterologous DNA encoding an Fab comprising a γ1λ subunit and expresses said γ1λ subunit on the surface thereof;
adding a magnetic label to cells bearing said antigen-bearing moiety on their surface;
incubating said phage display library with said magnetically labeled cells in the presence of an excess of non-labeled cells which do not express said antigen-bearing moiety to form a mixture, whereby said first and second virus vectors bind to said magnetically labeled cells;
isolating magnetically labeled cells from said mixture, whereby said first and second virus vectors are isolated from said mixture;
obtaining said first heterologous DNA from said first virus vector;
obtaining said second heterologous DNA from said second virus vector;
dissociating said first and second heterologous DNA using a restriction endonuclease and ligating at least the portion of said first heterologous DNA encoding said subunit and at least the portion of said second heterologous DNA encoding said different subunit to form a hybrid heterologous DNA;
generating a hybrid virus vector-comprising said hybrid heterologous DNA and expressing said subunit and said different subunit of said protein on the surface thereof;
adding a magnetic label to cells bearing said antigen-bearing moiety on their surface;
incubating said hybrid virus vector with said magnetically labeled cells in the presence of an excess of non-labeled cells which do not express said antigen-bearing moiety to form a mixture, whereby said hybrid virus vector binds to said magnetically labeled cells;
isolating magnetically labeled cells from said mixture, whereby said hybrid virus vector is isolated from said mixture; and
isolating said protein from said isolated virus vector, whereby said protein is isolated.

3. A method of isolating a DNA encoding a protein which binds to an antigen-bearing moiety, said method comprising
generating a phage display library comprising a plurality of virus vectors, wherein at least one of said virus vectors expresses said protein on the surface thereof and comprises said DNA, said DNA being heterologous with respect to said virus vector, wherein said phage display library is a shuffled Fab/phage display library, further wherein said shuffled Fab/phage display library is created from a first γκ display library and a second γλ phage display library;
adding a magnetic label to cells bearing said antigen-bearing moiety on their surface, thereby producing magnetically labeled cells;
incubating said phage display library with said magnetically labeled cells in the presence of an excess of unlabeled cells which do not express said antigen-bearing moiety to form a mixture, whereby said at least one virus vector binds to said magnetically labeled cells;
isolating magnetically labeled cells from said mixture, whereby said at least one virus vector is isolated from said mixture; and
obtaining DNA encoding said protein from said isolated virus vector.
